Trailer's nice. When I'm not distracted by those stupid, awful hats. I was actually excited to see it in theaters but it turned out to be so painful to sit through. Especially since nearly every character has some kind of ridiculous headgear. Poseidon's hat looks like someone's arts and craft project of a fish. Ares has that weird super mowhawk thing going on. And the minotaur is just a giant, shirtless dude wearing a hat that looks like a bull's head...MADE OF POISONED BARBED WIRE!! Watching the movie, you get the impression the film makers had heard of Greek mythology before, but couldn't be bothered to look it up. If you want stupid, sword and sandals fun, Clash of the Titans is a much better choice.
And have I mentioned how much I hate the stupid hats?

comments: one of the best movies i ever saw

The reason, I believe, why this film is so underrated (especially by audiences) is the fact that, much like Kubrick's "Barry Lyndon," it leans toward a more meditative style, reflecting and analyzing the psyche of its two lead characters rather than engaging in the typical gratuitous standoff/shootout sequences with rapid-fire editing, while also presenting its characters not as mythical figures (a common clich√© of the Western genre), but as simple, ordinary, flawed men who are not actually tough but just happen to be prone to violence and greed. Also, it's quite more leisurely paced than "There Will Be Blood" (an equally great picture) and less action-centered than "3:10 to Yuma" (a considerably inferior picture). In a nutshell, it's a masterpiece.

And then I saw this movie, didn't thought I could relate to that at all, but even though Maggie has parkinson, I could totally feel what she was going through. The shaking of parkinson, reminded me of my shaking when I get anxious or panic attacks in public. And that she didn't let anyone close to her in the fear someone might leave bc of her illness, it's the same for me to be honest. And this movie is so great and inspiring.
